Just because it's at the Four Seasons does not mean it's stuffy and pretentious.
Charlie Paler Steak has come into it's own and is now a great steak eatery.
Non steak eaters will not find much to eat (couple of fish dishes, a lobster, chicken breast, rack of lamb).
Yes it exudes elegance.
Yes the service is steakhouse proper versus steakhouse friendly.
It's steakhouse service that guys would be comfortable bringing their ladies to.
Straight forward steakhouse starters (oysters on the half shell, shellfish platter, prawn cocktail; nothing wrong, nothing stands out.
Excellent American Wagyu tartare with fried quail egg.
Hand cut beef, balanced seasoning.
Very good without being too cloying.
The pan seared foie is inventive.
The traditional sweetness and acidity is provided by a pineapple upside down cake and a strawberry gastrique.
Stunning.
Steak mains now impress.
The Kagoshima A5, yes A5 filet mignon ($40/oz four ounce minimum).
Eclipses the A4 quality at other top steakhouses.
Simply seared and seasoned with sea salt.
Sublime.
Sweet, clean beef flavor  and it literally melts in your mouth.
Think otoro tuna.
The wet aged USDA Prime charcoal grilled filet is excellent.
Extremely high heat charcoal creates the perfect crust.
The charcoal imparts a good smoky bitterness that elevates the sweetness of the usually boring cut.
Finally the 28 day dry aged porterhouse.
Well trimmed with a more mild umame finish.
Nutty but not much bleu cheese flavor.
Sides are steakhouse standard but the standout remains the twice baked truffle potato.
Seriously good eats that adds a deem earthy flavor and richness to any steak.
Why more steakhouses don't make twice baked potato is beyond me.
Not calorie counting and wanting to splurge?
Add seared foie or bone marrow to any steak and put it over the top.
Tip:  Do check out their prefix menus which include bottomless pour wine pairings.
Excellent wine list with many smaller, hard to get producers.
Good selection of pinot noir.
Typical Vegas resort pricing.
Kagoshima A5.
Ahhh.

